Democracy without peoplehood
Something has happened to democracy in the sense that the government is elected by the people, and this is true everywhere in the world.
In some way, people have lost faith in elections.
Voter turnout has been declining in many countries; in the case of the European Parliament elections, the voter turnout was so low that the legitimacy of the election results is in question.
Aside from voter turnout, we have become accustomed to accepting political parties or candidates who received 25% of the votes cast as "winners."
From Holland to Finland, and from Argentina to Japan, majority governments are formed based on minorities.
Even the apparent exceptions do not prove the opposite.
Only a few American presidents have been elected by more than 10% of the eligible voters. In fact, half of the eligible voters in the US have not even registered to vote; of those who did register, half did not vote; and of those who did vote, less than half voted for the winning candidate.
Even Tony Blair's "decisive" majority in the UK House of Commons is on shaky ground: the Labour Party received just over 40% of the votes in the last election in 2002, with a voter turnout of 60%.
Therefore, only 24% of the total electorate supported Blair's party.
In most countries, elections look much different now than they did twenty, or even fifty years ago.
What has happened?
One answer may be that voters distrust political parties.
Electoral democracy functions in most countries based on the mediation of organizations that put forward candidates who stand for specific packages of political options, for a "manifesto" or a "party program."
This long-established practice no longer works for a number of reasons.
Ideological party programs have lost their strength; voters no longer accept the packages imposed by the parties, they want to pick and choose their own preferences.
Furthermore, political parties have become machines composed of tightly organized cadres of insiders.
The paradox here is that the parties have become even more clique-like with the loss of their specific ideological orientation.
It is more important to belong to them than to share their specific beliefs.
Such developments have alienated the parties from the voter.
Because most people do not want to belong to any particular party, only a minority plays along with the party game anymore.
Thus, the public's suspicion of political parties increases even further, in part because, like in professional sports, it is expensive to participate.
If the costs are borne by taxpayers, it is taken very badly.
Yet without financial support from the state, parties would have to obtain money through channels that are often dubious, if not even illegal.
Many of the major political scandals of the past decades began with the financing of parties and their candidates.
Other evidence - such as the明显 decline in membership - confirms that parties have become unpopular.
Nevertheless, parties are indispensable for a electoral democracy.
The result is an obvious separation between the visible political actors and the electorate.
Because parties are active in parliaments, the effects of this separation affect one of the key institutions of democracy.
People no longer believe that parliaments represent them and therefore are not equipped with the necessary legitimacy to make decisions on their behalf.
At this point, a second, rather independent development comes into play.
People are today more impatient than ever before.
As consumers, they are accustomed to immediate satisfaction.
Yet as voters, they have to wait before they can feel the results of the election they cast at the ballot box.
Sometimes they never see the desired results.
Democracy needs time not only for elections, but also for discussions and careful consideration.
The consumer as a voter does not accept this and therefore turns away.
There are alternatives. However, each has its own problems as a democratic solution.
"Direct action" through demonstrations has become a regular and often effective event.
For less mobile people, it could be replaced by the possibility of expressing their opinion electronically; this ranges from internet chat rooms to electronic messages to political leaders.
Then there are also non-governmental organizations. They often have undemocratic structures, but seem to be still more closely connected to the citizens.
In addition, there is of course the possibility to completely switch off and leave politics to the experts, in order to focus on other aspects of life.
The latter probably carries the greatest risks, because it promotes the creeping authoritarianism that is a sign of our time.
But the other signs of the separation between politics and citizens also lead to a rather uncertain situation, because no one can anymore say how representative the prevailing opinions are.
Some would like to cut through the knot by means of more direct democracy.
But a lasting connection between leaders and the led cannot be established by reducing public discussion to simple voting alternatives.
There is still much to be said for holding fast to the classical institutions of parliamentary democracy and attempting to reconnect them more closely with the citizens.
After all, unpopular parties and declining voter turnout could turn out to be only a temporary phenomenon.
New parties could emerge and elections and representative governments could once again come to life.
Yet this is probably not enough to restore the general legitimacy that elected governments have lost.
Therefore, the first concern of all those who care about the constitution of freedom must be to rethink democracy and its institutions.
